For a 70B model at FP8 with 16k context, 200 concurrent sequences:

KV cache total: ~650 GB
Tier 0 (HBM): 218 GB → 70 hot sequences
Tier 1 (LPDDR): 432 GB → 140 warm sequences
Tier 2 (NVMe): only if additional overflow

This enables 128k context on a single NVL8 node for up to ~30 concurrent sessions,
vs ~8 on Blackwell without tiering.
2. AdaptiveParallelismPlanner
Automatically selects TP/PP/EP/DP configuration based on model size and cluster topology.
Key heuristics for Rubin:

TP ≤ 8 (NVSwitch group boundary — beyond here NVLink crosses switch)
PP across nodes only when inter-node bandwidth ≥ activation size × 2
EP = full expert count when experts ≤ total GPUs × 4

3. MultiTenantGpuScheduler
Priority-weighted fair-share scheduler with GPU block snapping (1/2/4/8 GPUs)
for NVLink-aware contiguous allocation.
4. PowerAwareConsolidationScheduler
At < 35% cluster utilization, migrates workloads and suspends idle nodes.
Estimated power saving: 1.76 kW per suspended NVL8 node (8 GPUs at idle).

Problem 4: Software Adoption Latency
The Gap
Rubin ships H2 2026. Based on Blackwell's experience, the software ecosystem
will lag 6–12 months behind hardware availability:

FP4 kernels: Rubin peak is NVFP4 (50 TFLOPS/GPU), but most production code
uses BF16. A model running BF16 on Rubin achieves ~25% of peak NVFP4 compute.
FP8 (Transformer Engine) achieves ~50%. Full FP4 requires CUTLASS FP4 or CUDA 13 support.
NVLink-C2C unified memory: Code that does explicit .cpu() copies wastes
3–5 µs per call — unnecessary when Vera and Rubin share an address space.
HBM4 bandwidth utilization: Old kernel tile sizes designed for HBM3e
(1.5 TB/s) are too small for HBM4 (22 TB/s). Optimal Triton tile sizes need
to be 2–4× larger to saturate bandwidth.
NCCL misconfiguration: Without NCCL_NVLS_ENABLE=1, in-switch reductions
(NVLink SHARP) are disabled, leaving ~15–20% collective performance on the table.
DataParallel anti-pattern: torch.nn.DataParallel doesn't understand
NVSwitch topology groups — it creates broadcast storms across all 72 GPUs
instead of using the 8-GPU NVSwitch locality.

Our Solution: rubin_adoption_profiler.py
Three-part tool:
A. Static Code Scanner
AST-based analysis of Python source code identifying 6 Rubin anti-patterns:
each with severity (BLOCKER/MAJOR/MINOR/INFO), category, explanation, and
a concrete code patch.
B. Roofline Estimator
Rubin-specific roofline model that takes FLOPs + bytes_accessed + dtype and returns:

Bottleneck identification (memory-bound vs compute-bound)
Efficiency ceiling (TFLOPS)
Specific migration path (BF16 → FP8 → FP4) with quantified gains

Example — Attention BF16 at 4k context:
AI = 94 FLOP/B < ridge 568 (BF16) → MEMORY BOUND
Ceiling = 2,068 TFLOPS (not 12,500 peak)
→ Switch to FP8: AI stays same, bytes halved → ceiling doubles
→ Fuse QKV + FlashAttention: data reuse doubles AI → push toward compute-bound
C. Config Generator
Outputs optimized configurations for:

Environment variables (NCCL NVLink 6, HBM4 allocator)
vLLM engine args (FP8 KV cache, BlueField-4 offload, batch coalescing)
Triton autotune configs (larger tiles, SM cluster hints, pipeline depth)
torch.distributed device_mesh for NVSwitch-aware TP groups

Projected adoption acceleration: Teams using the profiler can identify and
fix the top 3 performance blockers in < 1 day, vs 2–4 weeks of manual profiling.
This translates to realizing the full 3.3–5× Rubin speedup within weeks of
hardware availability rather than months.

